    56 Chapter 3: 3-D Sheet Metal Forming Results Main Index Figure 3-6 Various Deformed Stages during Spring Back Step In the analysis without friction, contact is initially present between the sheet and the lower section of the punch. Near the end of the deformation, the sheet separates at the lower section of the punch and gets in contact with the lower section of the die. As soon as this contact is detected, the sheet is further bent into the final shape and the required force in the force displacement history curve increases ( Figure 3-5). In the analysis with friction, the deformation behavior is different. The tangential forces due to friction result in a stretching of the sheet causing contact between the punch and the sheet to be present during the complete forming history. The characteristic load displacement curves for the analysis from SOL 400 without friction and with friction are shown in Figure 3-7. The differences in the shape of the curves are caused by the different contact conditions at the end of the forming stage.

    MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems Results57 Main Index Figure 3-7 Load Displacement Diagram for 2-D Plane Strain Model Observe that the unloading stage is analyzed in two steps. In the first unloading step the punch and the strip are moved simultaneously in upward direction. This releases the strip from the die, while it remains in contact with the punch. In the second unloading step the strip is fixed in vertical direction while the punch is moved further upward to its original position. This gradually releases the strip from the punch and allows it to spring back to its final configuration. Note that the fixation of the strip is such that there are no reaction forces after it has lost contact with both the die and the punch. This, of course, is a requirement in order to capture the proper spring back behavior. The fixation primarily serves to suppress rigid body motions of the model during the unloading stage. The characteristic values of the angles at the end of the forming stage and after removal of the tool are listed in Table 3-4. In the last figure, a comparison is also made with the experimental result. The results from SOL 400 are found to be on the higher side, particularly towards the end of forming. The results exhibit more oscillations in the load displacement curve and this is caused by the use of hard contact approach in Marc and SOL 400. Modeling Tips One of the complicating characteristics in this benchmark problem is a very local contact between the plate and the curved shoulders of the die. In fact, the contact is almost a point (2-D) or line (3-D) contact with a large amount of sliding. Contact is only verified between the nodes of the plate and the rigid dies. The following are some guidelines and tips for modeling this benchmark: ï®A fine mesh has to be used to describe the contact of the nodes of the sheet with the die properly ï®A smooth representation of the die has to be chosen, either in an analytical form or by a piecewise linear curve using a high number of segments ï®The unloading behavior is characterized by removal of the tools and at the same time adding boundary conditions preventing the possibility of rigid body movement. ï®The unloading behavior should preferably be done in a number of steps. Note that in these steps low values of the normal and, consequently, the friction forces are present which makes it difficult to obtain a converged solution ï®Numerical damping is often recommended to stabilize the solution, but it can be shown that this greatly influences the accuracy of the solution.     72 Chapter 5: Steel Roller on Rubber Introduction Main Index Introduction If a cylindrical steel roller rotates on a rubber base, it will have moved a distance less than the circumference of cylinder for a complete rotation of the cylinder. This is due to the effect of friction and stretch of rubber under the stresses induced by cylinder. Osborne Reynolds demonstrated this phenomenon in 1874. This contact benchmark will test the ability of solver algorithms to model the movement of the two surfaces when they are in contact, as the rubber will stretch compared to the steel cylinder.Displacement Boundary conditionsDisplacement History ï®Centre of the roller is fixed in horizontal and vertical directions ï®Time period 0-1 second: â€¢no rotation of roller â€¢move bottom surface of rubber 3 mm up â€¢sheet x-displacement fixed ï®Time period 1-2 second â€¢prescribed rotation of steel roller (360 degrees) â€¢bottom surface of rubber sheet held at 3 mm y-displacement â€¢sheet is free to move in horizontal direction Applied loads No applied loads Element type 2D Simulation ï®Plane strain-4 noded quadrilateral (CQUAD4) elements 3D Simulation ï®Solid 8-noded hexahedral (CHEXA) ï®Mix of solid 8-noded hexahedral (CHEXA) and 5 noded pyramid (CPYRA) elements Contact properties 1.Rolling contact of steel roller with rubber 2.Rotating rigid body is glued to the steel roller 3.Bilinear Coulomb friction with coefficient of friction = 0.3 4.Both node to segment and segment to segment contacts are considered.     MSC Nastran Demonstration Problems Solution Requirements73 Main Index Solution Requirements The cylindrical roller with radius 30 mm is rotating over 360 degrees. The circumference of the cylinder is 188.5 mm. Point A is the point on the rubber sheet just below the lowest point of the steel cylinder at the start of the analysis. The displacement component of this point in the x-direction needs to be determined from this study. Following different 2D and 3D models are considered for this benchmark. 1.Plane strain model simulated with 4 noded quadrilateral 2D continuum elements for both steel roller and rubber. 2.Solid model simulated with 8 noded hexahedral 3D continuum elements for both steel roller and rubber. 3.Solid model simulated with 8 noded hexahedral 3D continuum elements for steel roller and with a mix of 8 noded hexahedral and 5 noded pyramid 3D continuum elements for rubber.
